1 A BILL TO BE ENTITLED
2 AN ACT TO MAKE VARIOUS CHANGES TO THE PRINCIPAL FELLOWS PROGRAM
3 AND TO CODIFY ADMINISTRATIVE INTERNSHIP STIPENDS.
4 The General Assembly of North Carolina enacts:
5
6 PART I. MODIFY ALLOWABLE USES OF FUNDS FOR THE PRINCIPAL FELLOWS
7 PROGRAM
8 SECTION 1. Article 5C of Chapter 116 of the General Statutes reads as rewritten:
9 "Article 5C.
10 "North Carolina Principal Fellows Program.
11 "§ 116-74.41. North Carolina Principal Fellows Commission established; membership.
12 (a) There is established the North Carolina Principal Fellows Commission. The
13 Commission shall exercise its powers and duties independently in its administration of the North
14 Carolina Principal Fellows Program in accordance with this Article. The Director of the Program
15 shall staff the Commission in accordance with G.S. 116-74.49. The State Education Assistance
16 Authority as created in G.S. 116-203 shall be is responsible for awarding grants upon selection
17 of the recipients by the Commission in accordance with G.S. 116-74.46 and G.S. 116-74.46A
18 and executing agreements for forgivable scholarship loans, cancelling through service,
19 collecting, and otherwise enforcing the agreements under G.S. 116-74.48.
20 …
21 "§ 116-74.41A. Definitions.
22 For the purposes of this Article, the following definitions apply:
23 (1) Authority or SEAA. – The State Education Assistance Authority as created in
24 G.S. 116-203.
25 (2) Commission. – The North Carolina Principal Fellows Commission.
26 (2a) Developmental grant. – A grant awarded to an eligible entity pursuant to
27 G.S. 116-74.46A.
28 (3) Eligible entity. – A for-profit or nonprofit organization or an institution of
29 higher education that has an evidence-based plan for preparing school leaders
30 who implement school leadership practices linked to increased student
31 achievement.
32 (4) High-need local school administrative unit. – A local school administrative
33 unit with the majority of its schools deemed to be high-need schools as defined
34 in subdivision (5) of this subsection.
35 (5) High-need school. – A public school that meets one or more of the following
36 criteria:
*H1143-v-2*

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 a. Is a school identified under Part A of Title I of the Elementary and
2 Secondary Education Act of 1965, as amended.
3 b. Is a persistently low-achieving school, as identified by the Department
4 of Public Instruction for purposes of federal accountability.
5 c. A middle school containing any of grades five through eight that feeds
6 into a high school with less than a seventy-five percent (75%)
7 four-year cohort graduation rate.
8 d. A high school with less than a seventy-five percent (75%) four-year
9 cohort graduation rate.
10 (6) Repealed by Session Laws 2019-60, s. 1(x), effective July 1, 2021.
11 (7) Principal. – The highest administrative official in a public school building
12 with primary responsibility for the instructional leadership, talent
13 management, and organizational development of the school.
14 (7a) Principal Fellows grant. – A grant awarded to an eligible entity pursuant to
15 G.S. 116-74.46.
16 (8) Repealed by Session Laws 2019-60, s. 1(x), effective July 1, 2021.
17 (9) Program. – The North Carolina Principal Fellows Program established
18 pursuant to G.S. 116-74.44.
19 (9a) Program participant. – An individual enrolled at an eligible entity that has
20 been awarded a Principal Fellows grant.
21 (10) Public school. – An elementary or secondary school located in North Carolina
22 that is operated by a local board of education, charter school board of
23 directors, regional school board of directors, chancellor for a University of
24 North Carolina laboratory school, an innovative school operator, or the United
25 States government.
26 (11) School leader. – An individual employed in a school leadership role, including
27 principal or assistant principal roles.
28 (12) Student achievement. – At the whole school level, after three years of leading
29 a school, consistent and methodologically sound measures of:
30 a. Student academic achievement.
31 b. Aggregated individual student academic growth.
32 c. Additional outcomes, such as high school graduation rates, the
33 percentage of students taking advanced-level coursework, or the
34 percentage of students who obtain a career-related credential through
35 a national business certification exam.
36 (13) Trust Fund. – The North Carolina Principal Fellows Trust Fund established
37 pursuant to G.S. 116-74.41B.
38 "§ 116-74.41B. The North Carolina Principal Fellows Trust Fund.
39 (a) Trust Fund Established. – The North Carolina Principal Fellows Trust Fund shall be
40 an institutional trust fund established pursuant to G.S. 116-36.1. All funds appropriated to, or
41 otherwise received by, (i) the Program for the award of Principal Fellows grants pursuant to
42 G.S. 116-74.44, and developmental grants, (ii) all funds received as repayment of scholarship
43 loans, including under the former Principal Fellows Program administered under G.S. 116-74.42
44 and the Transforming Principal Preparation Program under G.S. 116-209.77, and (iii) all interest
45 earned on these funds shall be placed in the Trust Fund.
46 (b) Use of Monies in the Trust Fund. – The monies in the Trust Fund may be used only
47 for the purposes set forth in this subsection, including the award of Principal Fellows grants
48 pursuant to G.S. 116-74.44, and developmental grants, administrative costs, and costs associated
49 with Program operations in accordance with this Article. The Authority may use up to two
50 percent (2%) of the funds appropriated for the Program or one hundred sixty thousand dollars
51 ($160,000) from the Trust Fund, whichever is greater, each fiscal year for administrative costs,
Page 2 House Bill 1143-Second Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 including recovery of funds advanced under the Program, and may allocate to the Commission
2 up to eight hundred thousand dollars ($800,000) from the Trust Fund each fiscal year for the
3 following:
4 (1) The salary and benefits of the director and staff of the Program.
5 (2) The expenses of the Commission to administer the Program.
6 (3) Program monitoring and evaluation.
7 (4) Extracurricular enhancement activities for the Program.
8 (5) Repealed by Session Laws 2019-60, s. 1(y), effective July 1, 2021.
9 (6) Programming on research-based school leadership practices to be shared with
10 eligible entities in order to improve principal preparation throughout the State.
11 (c) Remaining Funds. – If at the end of each fiscal year there are funds remaining in the
12 Trust Fund that are not obligated or otherwise encumbered for another purpose, upon the request
13 of the Commission, the Authority shall allocate the funds to the Commission for any of the
14 purposes identified in subdivisions (3) through (6) of subsection (b) of this section.
15 …
16 "§ 116-74.44. North Carolina Principal Fellows Program established; administration.
17 (a) Established. – There is established the North Carolina Principal Fellows Program as
18 a competitive grant program for eligible entities for the purpose of elevating educators in North
19 Carolina public schools by transforming the preparation of principals across the State and
20 providing for forgivable scholarship loans to the participants of those school leader preparation
21 programs. The Authority shall administer the North Carolina Principal Fellows Program in
22 collaboration with the Commission as set forth in this Article to provide funds for the preparation
23 and support of highly effective future school principals in North Carolina.
24 (b) Program Administration. – The Commission shall select grant recipients recipients of
25 Principal Fellows grants and developmental grants and notify the Authority for the award of the
26 grants with the Authority acting as the fiscal agent for the Trust Fund with respect to grants
27 awarded by the Commission. The Commission shall also coordinate with Principal Fellows grant
28 recipients to provide extracurricular enhancement activities for program participants. The
29 Authority shall monitor the implementation of forgivable scholarship loans to school leader
30 preparation program participants, as authorized by this Article.
31 (c) Administration of Forgivable Scholarship Loans. – Upon the Principal Fellows grant
32 recipients' selection of the program participants for the school leader preparation programs, the
33 Commission shall transfer the names of all program participants to the Authority. The Authority
34 shall perform all of the administrative functions necessary to implement the forgivable
35 scholarship loans to the school leader preparation program participants, which functions shall
36 include rulemaking, disseminating information, acting as a liaison with participating eligible
37 entities, implementing forgivable loan agreements in the form of promissory notes, monitoring
38 loan repayment through service and cash, and performing all other functions necessary for the
39 execution, payment, and enforcement of promissory notes required under this Article.
40 (d) Prior Loan Monitoring. – The Authority, in collaboration with the Commission, shall
41 also monitor the implementation of forgivable scholarship loans to school leader preparation
42 program participants executed pursuant to G.S. 116-209.77, and the Authority shall administer
43 all outstanding forgivable scholarship loans previously awarded and subject to repayment under
44 the former Transforming Principal Preparation Program administered pursuant to Part 4 of
45 Article 23 of this Chapter.
46 "§ 116-74.45. Grant Principal Fellows grant applications; priority.
47 (a) Application Requirements. – Subject to the availability of funds for this purpose, the
48 Commission shall issue a request for proposal with guidelines and criteria for applying for a
49 Principal Fellows grant. An eligible entity that seeks a Principal Fellows grant shall submit to the
50 Commission an application at such time, in such manner, and accompanied by such information
51 as the Commission may require. Eligible entities may create partnerships to develop and establish
House Bill 1143-Second Edition Page 3

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 school leader preparation programs and apply jointly to be a grant recipient. An applicant shall
2 include at least the following information in its application for consideration by the Commission:
3 …
4 (b) Application Priority. – The Commission shall evaluate the applicants for Principal
5 Fellows grants by giving priority to an eligible entity with a record of preparing principals
6 demonstrating the following:
7 (1) Improvement in student achievement.
8 (2) Placement as school leaders in eligible schools.
9 (3) A proposed focus on and, if applicable, a record of serving high-need schools,
10 high-need local school administrative units, or both.
11 (4) A detailed plan and commitment to share lessons learned and to improve the
12 capacity of other entities in reaching similar outcomes.
13 (5) A service area that is underserved by existing principal preparation programs
14 or demonstrates unmet need despite current available programs.
15 "§ 116-74.46. Recipient Principal Fellows grant recipient selection; use of grant funds;
16 duration and conditions of grants; reporting requirements.
17 (a) Selection. – After evaluation of Principal Fellows grant applications pursuant to
18 G.S. 116-74.45, the Commission shall notify the Authority of its selection of the recipients of
19 Principal Fellows grants for each fiscal year. The Commission shall select up to eight Principal
20 Fellows grant recipients to be operating a school leader preparation program with grant funds in
21 any fiscal year.
22 (b) Use of Funds. – Each eligible entity that receives Principal Fellows grant funds shall
23 use those funds to carry out the following:
24 (1) Recruiting and selecting, based on a rigorous evaluation of the competencies
25 of the school leader candidates participating in the program and their potential
26 and desire to become effective school leaders.
27 (2) Operating a school leader preparation program that provides the opportunity
28 for all candidates to earn a master's degree, if they do not already have one,
29 and subsequent principal licensure by doing the following:
30 a. Utilizing a research-based content and curriculum, including
31 embedded participant assessments to evaluate candidates before
32 program completion that prepares candidates to do the following:
33 1. Provide instructional leadership, such as developing teachers'
34 instructional practices and analyzing classroom and
35 school-wide data to support teachers.
36 2. Manage talent, such as developing a high-performing team.
37 3. Build a positive school culture, such as building a strong school
38 culture focused on high academic achievement for all students,
39 including gifted and talented students, students with
40 disabilities, and English learners; maintaining active
41 engagement with family and community members; and
42 ensuring student safety.
43 4. Develop organizational practices, such as aligning staff,
44 budget, and time to the instructional priorities of the school.
45 b. Providing opportunities for sustained and high-quality job-embedded
46 practice in an authentic setting where candidates are responsible for
47 moving the practice and performance of a subset of teachers or for
48 school-wide performance as principal-in-planning or interim school
49 leaders.
50 (3) Collecting data on program implementation and program completer outcomes
51 for continuous program improvement.
