1 (4) Covering the cost of attendance and completion for program participants for
2 the school leader preparation program from the funds received on behalf of
3 program participants through forgivable scholarship loans issued in
4 accordance with the requirements of G.S. 116-74.48.
5 (c) Duration and Conditions of Principal Fellows Grants. – The Commission shall also
6 notify the Authority of its decisions on the duration and renewal of Principal Fellows grants to
7 eligible entities made in accordance with the following:
8 …
9 (d) Reporting Requirements for Grant Recipients. – Recipients of Principal Fellows
10 grants shall participate in all evaluation activities required by the Commission and submit an
11 annual report to the Commission with any information requested by the Commission. The
12 recipients shall comply with additional report requests made by the Commission. Whenever
13 practicable and within a reasonable amount of time, grant recipients shall also make all materials
14 developed as part of the program and with Principal Fellows grant funds publicly available to
15 contribute to the broader sharing of promising practices. Materials shall not include personally
16 identifiable information regarding individuals involved or associated with the program,
17 including, without limitation, applicants, participants, supervisors, evaluators, faculty, and staff,
18 without their prior written consent. The Commission shall work with recipients, local school
19 administrative units, and public schools, as needed, to enable the collection, analysis, and
20 evaluation of at least the following relevant data, within necessary privacy constraints:
21 …
22 "§ 116-74.46A. Developmental grants.
23 (a) Selection. – Subject to the availability of funds after awarding Principal Fellows
24 grants, the Commission may select up to two eligible entities that did not receive Principal
25 Fellows grants to receive a one-year developmental grant of up to two hundred fifty thousand
26 dollars ($250,000) per recipient. The Commission shall notify the Authority of selected
27 developmental grant recipients for each fiscal year.
28 (b) Use of Funds. – An eligible entity that receives a developmental grant may use those
29 funds for any of the permissible uses of a Principal Fellows grant in G.S. 116-74.46(b) except
30 for covering the cost of attendance and completion for program participants under
31 G.S. 116-74.46(b)(4).
32 (c) Renewal. – The Commission may renew a developmental grant up to five times based
33 on compliance with the grant terms and performance. The Commission shall notify the Authority
34 of its decisions on the renewal of developmental grants.
35 (d) Reporting Requirements for Grant Recipients. – Recipients of developmental grants
36 shall participate in all evaluation activities required by the Commission and, for each year in
37 which developmental grants are received, submit a report to the Commission with any
38 information requested by the Commission. The recipients shall comply with additional report
39 requests made by the Commission.
40 "§ 116-74.47. Reports.
41 The Commission shall provide the State Board of Education, the Authority, and the Joint
42 Legislative Education Oversight Committee with the data collected from grant recipients in
43 accordance with G.S. 116-74.46 and G.S. 116-74.46A on an annual basis.
44 "§ 116-74.48. Terms of forgivable scholarship loans for program recipients.
45 (a) Notes. – A program participant shall be is eligible for a forgivable scholarship loan in
46 the amount of up to twenty thousand dollars ($20,000) per year for up to two years in the program,
47 with a maximum loan amount of forty thousand dollars ($40,000) per participant. All forgivable
48 scholarship loans for school leader preparation program participants shall be evidenced by notes
49 made payable to the Authority that bear interest at a rate not to exceed ten percent (10%) per year
50 as set by the Authority and beginning 90 days after completion of the school leader preparation
51 program, or 90 days after termination of the loan, whichever is earlier. The funds from the
House Bill 1143-Second Edition Page 5

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 forgivable scholarship loan shall be disbursed directly to the Principal Fellows grantee on behalf
2 of the recipient for participation in the school leader preparation program. The forgivable
3 scholarship loan may be terminated upon the recipient's withdrawal from the preparation program
4 or by the recipient's failure to meet the standards set by the Commission or the Principal Fellows
5 grantee.
6 …
7 (c) Repayment Period. – The Authority, in collaboration with the Commission and
8 Principal Fellows grantees, shall monitor the acceptability of service repayment agreements and
9 compliance of the recipient with the agreement. The Commission shall notify the Authority of
10 any relevant information or change in the circumstances pertaining to the recipient impacting the
11 enforcement of the promissory note. A forgivable scholarship loan shall also be forgiven if the
12 Commission finds it is impossible for the recipient to work for four years as a school
13 administrator, within seven years after completion of the preparation program supported by the
14 loan, because of the death or permanent disability of the recipient. If the recipient repays the
15 forgivable scholarship loan by cash payments to the Authority, all indebtedness shall be repaid
16 within 10 years after completion of the school leader preparation program supported by the loan.
17 If the recipient completes the school leader preparation program, payment of principal and
18 interest shall begin no later than 27 months after the completion of the program. Should a
19 recipient present extenuating circumstances, the Authority may extend the period to repay the
20 forgivable scholarship loan in cash to no more than a total of 12 years.
21 "§ 116-74.49. Staff to the Commission.
22 The Commission shall appoint a director of the North Carolina Principal Fellows Program.
23 The director shall chair and staff the Commission and shall administer the extracurricular
24 enhancement activities of the Program. The University of North Carolina System Office shall
25 provide office space for the Program. The office space shall not be located on the campus of a
26 constituent institution."
27
28 PART II. APPROPRIATION FOR PRINCIPAL FELLOWS PROGRAM
29 SECTION 2. There is appropriated from the General Fund to the North Carolina
30 Principal Fellows Trust Fund the sum of five million dollars ($5,000,000) in recurring funds
31 beginning in the 2026-2027 fiscal year to increase the number of Principal Fellows candidates
32 supported by the North Carolina Principal Fellows Program in accordance with Article 5C of
33 Chapter 116 of the General Statutes. These funds shall be allocated as follows:
34 (1) The sum of two million six hundred thousand dollars ($2,600,000) to be used
35 to bring the number of Principal Fellows candidates receiving funds in the
36 2028-2034 award cycle into parity with the number of recipients in other
37 award cycles.
38 (2) The sum of two million four hundred thousand dollars ($2,400,000) to expand
39 the number of Principal Fellows candidates supported by the Program with
40 the goal of having fifty-five percent (55%) of all principals employed in North
41 Carolina be graduates of the North Carolina Principal Fellows Program.
42
43 PART III. ADMINISTRATIVE INTERNSHIP STIPENDS
44 SECTION 3. Article 19 of Chapter 115C of the General Statutes is amended by
45 adding the following new section to read:
46 "§ 115C-284.2. Administrative internship stipends.
47 (a) Definitions. – The following definitions apply in this section:
48 (1) Administrative intern. – A participant enrolled full time in an approved
49 administrator preparation program who is completing a full-time internship
50 pursuant to G.S. 115C-284.1(d)(1).
Page 6 House Bill 1143-Second Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (2) Administrator preparation program or APP. – As defined in
2 G.S. 115C-284.1(a).
3 (b) Stipend. – To the extent funds are made available for this purpose, the Department of
4 Public Instruction shall provide administrative interns with a 10-month stipend during the
5 internship that is the higher of the following:
6 (1) The beginning salary of an assistant principal.
7 (2) For a teacher who becomes an administrative intern, the salary the person
8 would earn as a teacher on the teacher salary schedule.
9 (c) If the funds made available for the stipends required by this section are insufficient to
10 fully fund the stipends, the Department of Public Instruction may use funds appropriated to the
11 State Public School Fund for this purpose.
12 (d) The North Carolina Principal Fellows Program or the APP where the administrative
13 intern is enrolled shall provide the Department of Public Instruction with certification of eligible
14 administrative interns in order to receive the stipends provided pursuant to this section.
15 (e) Report. – No later than February 15 of each year, the Department of Public Instruction
16 shall report to the Joint Legislative Education Oversight Committee on the stipends provided
17 pursuant to this section, including at least the following information:
18 (1) Demographic information of administrative interns.
19 (2) Total number of administrative interns.
20 (3) Number of administrative interns who are participating in the North Carolina
21 Principal Fellows Program.
22 (4) Number of administrative interns by APP.
23 (5) Number of administrative interns who serve as an assistant principal or
24 principal in a public school unit within five years of completing the internship,
25 disaggregated based on whether the intern participated in the North Carolina
26 Principal Fellows Program."
27
28 PART IV. EFFECTIVE DATE
29 SECTION 4. This act becomes effective July 1, 2026.
